## `<file-level: imports>`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-open-1 -->

### Purpose
Tests for `open()` flag semantics: `O_CREAT`, `O_EXCL`, `O_TRUNC`, `O_APPEND`, `O_RDONLY`/`O_WRONLY`/`O_RDWR`, `O_NOFOLLOW`. Ignored-by-design flags (`O_DIRECT`, `O_SYNC`, `O_NONBLOCK`) are also covered — a test asserts they are accepted and behave equivalently to the no-flag case (our `synchronous=FULL` means we are always durable; direct-IO has no meaning against SQLite).

### Implementation Notes

```python
import os
import pytest

from sqlite_fs.errors import (
    AlreadyExists,
    NotFound,
    PermissionDenied,
    SymlinkLoop,
)
```

---

## `test_open_rdonly_on_existing(as_root)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-open-2 -->

### Postconditions

```python
fd = as_root.create("/a")
as_root.write(fd, b"x", offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)

fd = as_root.open("/a", flags=os.O_RDONLY)
assert as_root.read(fd, size=1, offset=0) == b"x"
# Write under RDONLY fd raises PermissionDenied.
with pytest.raises(PermissionDenied):
    as_root.write(fd, b"y", offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)
```

---

