## `test_open_trunc_requires_write(as_root)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-open-10 -->

### Purpose
`O_TRUNC` with `O_RDONLY` is technically undefined per POSIX. Most systems ignore it; Linux truncates. We choose the Linux behavior: truncate happens regardless of access mode (a permission check for write-to-the-inode is still applied, so callers without write perm on the file still fail).

### Postconditions

```python
fd = as_root.create("/a", mode=0o644)
as_root.write(fd, b"x" * 100, offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)

fd = as_root.open("/a", flags=os.O_RDONLY | os.O_TRUNC)
assert as_root.stat("/a").size == 0
as_root.close_fd(fd)
```

---

## `test_open_append_noop_at_library(as_root)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-open-11 -->

### Purpose
Our library's `write(fd, data, offset)` takes an explicit offset — there is no "current position" the library maintains. `O_APPEND` is recorded on the fd (visible via the fd-table introspection used only by tests) so the FUSE adapter can honor it, but has no effect at the library layer. This test documents the contract.

### Postconditions

```python
fd = as_root.create("/a")
as_root.write(fd, b"start", offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)

fd = as_root.open("/a", flags=os.O_WRONLY | os.O_APPEND)

# Write at offset 0 — O_APPEND does NOT force the offset to EOF at library level.
as_root.write(fd, b"X", offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)

fd = as_root.open("/a", flags=os.O_RDONLY)
data = as_root.read(fd, size=100, offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)
# Byte 0 is "X" — the library did NOT redirect to EOF.
assert data == b"Xtart"

# But the fd table recorded the append flag.
# (Inspection via library's private hook.)
```

---

## `test_open_nofollow_on_symlink_raises(as_root)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-open-12 -->

### Purpose
`O_NOFOLLOW` causes `open` on a symlink to fail rather than follow it. This is how `openat(..., O_NOFOLLOW)` + `fchown` combine safely against TOCTOU attacks.

### Postconditions

```python
fd = as_root.create("/target"); as_root.close_fd(fd)
as_root.symlink(b"/target", "/link")

with pytest.raises(SymlinkLoop):
    # We reuse SymlinkLoop for "refused to follow" here; POSIX ELOOP.
    as_root.open("/link", flags=os.O_RDONLY | os.O_NOFOLLOW)

# Without O_NOFOLLOW, open follows normally.
fd = as_root.open("/link", flags=os.O_RDONLY)
as_root.close_fd(fd)
```

---

## `test_open_direct_sync_nonblock_accepted_silently(as_root)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-open-13 -->

### Purpose
`O_DIRECT`, `O_SYNC`, `O_NONBLOCK` are documented as ignored — they do not raise, and they do not change behavior. Our `synchronous=FULL` makes `O_SYNC` redundant; we don't implement non-blocking I/O.

### Postconditions

```python
fd = as_root.create("/a")
as_root.write(fd, b"x", offset=0)
as_root.close_fd(fd)

# All three flags on open — no error, behavior identical to plain O_RDONLY.
flags = os.O_RDONLY | os.O_DIRECT | os.O_SYNC | os.O_NONBLOCK
fd = as_root.open("/a", flags=flags)
assert as_root.read(fd, size=1, offset=0) == b"x"
as_root.close_fd(fd)
```

---

